@node Right-hand fingerings
@unnumberedsubsubsec Right-hand fingerings

@cindex fretted instrument, right-hand fingering
@cindex fingering, right-hand, for fretted instruments
@cindex right-hand fingering, for fretted instruments

@funindex \rightHandFinger

Right-hand fingerings @var{p-i-m-a} must be entered using
@code{\rightHandFinger} followed by a number.

@warning{If the number is entered in Scheme notation, remember to append
a space before following it with a closing @code{>} or similar.}

@lilypond[quote,verbatim,fragment]
\clef "treble_8"
c4\rightHandFinger 1
e\rightHandFinger 2
g\rightHandFinger 3
c'\rightHandFinger 4
<c\rightHandFinger 1 e\rightHandFinger 2
 g\rightHandFinger 3 c'\rightHandFinger 4 >1
@end lilypond

For convenience, @code{\rightHandFinger} may be abbreviated to something
shorter, for example @code{\RH}, by adding the appropriate definition
at the source file's top level:

@example
RH = \rightHandFinger \etc
@end example

Most behaviors of right-hand fingerings (namely, the @code{StrokeFinger}
object) may be set in the same way as ordinary fingerings: see
@ref{Fingering instructions}.

